print_settings.Notes:: I did this in PLA so it was designed for very little flexibility.  Tolerances are tight ~approx. .5mm.  Careful on printing the vertical column locks, if the heatbed is too hot you'll experience "elephant foot" and the locks will be very tight (not necessarily a bad thing but shouldn't be so tight that you need pliers to get apart).  I had a tough time with the horizontal locks due to gravity.  I incorporated a slight arch in the receptacles.  At the time I was using Cura 21.08 and those locks fit tight!  I've downloaded Cura 2.26 and that software actually seems to keep to the tolerances slightly better, my horizontal locks were slightly loose when printing with that version.  If printing with PLA I recommend setting the build plate temperature to 55C and part removal of 50C.  60C makes it awfully tough to remove the big parts with lots of surface area.  I've had excellent results with 55/50.

description.text:
This is a 3D printed Retro Style Game Controller Box for the Raspberry Pi. This was designed for smaller 3D printers (less than 200cm build plate) and to be 3D printed without having to use 'supports'. I also designed it so that there wasn't any external fasteners (like a snap together model) other than screw holes to screw in the Raspberry Pi, speaker and joystick.

I also designed this for use with the Arcade Bonnet from Adafruit. I did this so I could have sound from the arcade controller and not the display device (T.V., Monitor, LED panels, etc..). Also designed so I could use Arcade style buttons (30mm) and to utilize an actual joystick instead of a small 2 axis thumb type joystick. Some games just need the real thing!

Unfortunately the depth of the joystick and the buttons bumped up against the speaker and Raspberry Pi (with the arcade bonnet) forced me to raise the height of the box, so that's why its so tall. The buttons would short out against the arcade bonnet and kept rebooting.

The speaker's mounts was purposely split across the two main bodies to help keep the two halves of the controller box together.

comments.text: I have read reviews of the A3 and looked at some You Tube review of the A3 and several commented on the stability. I had a flat / solid doors from some old kitchen cabinets so I cut one to fit under the A3 with about an inch to spare all the way around. When I built y machine I drilled holes in the bottom of the frame and attached screws down through into the wood. Solid as a rock. Almost. The bottom will still flex. the only way to cure this is it make a flange around the base where the covers for the motherboard and PS are located and screw those covers to the bottom.  That would really stiffen things up. I haven't done it yet because I don't have a problem of movement when the machine is running. I only notice it when I lean on the top part when making adjustments etc.  Even then it will only flex about .030".  I use a dial gauge attached to a mount across the X rails that I made to measure bed flatness.

title: Aurora A3 Platform Base and Wire Protector

description.text:
This is support for the motors and base of the JG Aurora A3 printer because of the way the printer flexes in height around the X axis.

Also, with my cables for the hot bed would catch on the rear motor and rod support, I added a housing to smooth the cable while it moves back and forth while printing.

Printer:

JG Aurora A3

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The raft is most helpful for the largest piece since there is a weak spot and supports.

I set the support for 60 degree overhangs.

If I printed again, I would print with 0.2mm resolution so that it will print faster.

Please note that the "complete" file is just to show how the parts fit together. It is not printed. I printed the other four parts, one by one.

Assembly of Parts

Please note that the motor support part and the base support part loosely interlock. The "clip" part on the base support needs to be slid over the back lip of the base, and then the motor support can be slid under the printer's motor and "interlocked."

Motor Support

When placing the support parts under the motors, I realized that the motors are different heights above the table; thus, one needs to either place a shim under one or both motors, or one needs to loosen the motor bolts inside the housing to make them equal height. If you loosen the motor bolts, don't forget to re-level the hot bed.

Re-level hot bed

After placing the parts under the printer, it mostly likely need to be re-leveled because the front is no longer resting on the table, but raised to be able to move when the printer flexes.

Video Review Showed Problems With Printer Housing Flexing

When I saw a video review of the A3 printer flexing, I started trying to figure out how to fix or lessen the problem. Then I saw the motor supports for the A3 on this thingverse site: JG Aurora A3 Stable Feet by CdRsKuLL. I thought I could get away from the motor support, I designed just the support under the base on the printer. After seeing the printer not balancing correct, I added the motor support. I wanted to minimize the foot print of the motor support so I added a post in the top center of the motor support to keep the printer from vibrating off the support.

After that was working, I realized I can attach the curved support for the hot bed wires to the base support to make the wires move smoothly instead of catching slightly.

description.text:
Flower Lamp

This Lamp is inspired by a flower
The main body is made out of two parts printed in spiral vase mode.
The first part is green and acts as a basis.
The second part is red and acts as the blossom part.
Inside this red blossom part the LED’s are situated.
The light effects are partially created by three separated LED’s
One LED is red, one green and one is blue. In this case I used 1watt LED’s.
Then these LED’s are separated from each other with equal distance from each other.
Also these LED’s are glued with thermal compound to an aluminum plate that fits into the red blossom part.
This is for cooling and to keep them apart.
I will make a model of this LED part soon in the future, because people keep asking how it works.
Because I like to experiment with light, I made it so, that you can put other lampshades ore objects into the blossom parts.
This creates a lot of cool light effects, which are ever changing depending on the form of the placed objects.
I tried to capture these effects on the photos.But it loses a lot on the photos …
There are some shots of the sealing also. Also I added some photos of the flower lamp with some other objects and lamp shades in it.
I experimented with lampshades and vases that are posted already and there are 2 that I didn’t post
(the one in the photos that is printed in translucent PET-G and the one printed in translucent transparent PET-G).
They are also included as optional STL files.
But of course you can also use this lamp in its basic form or make your own custom lamp :-) .

title: Highly Configurable Carabiner (One Link To Rule Them All)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a highly configurable, parametric carabiner (karabiner). You put in the most meaningful dimensions (like the length, diameters of the ends, and width of the gaps -- and many others) and it does all the math. You can do quite a lot of wacky shapes with it.
One of the photos shows most of the parameters and what they affect. The code and parameters are fully commented, and there are several examples (the ones pictured) included in the code file as well. 
You can render with or without a clasp, with or without a sleeve, and with a variety of profiles, affecting the legs and ends independently. 
I plan to update this with an extra clasp style or two, but I wanted to get this out there in the meantime.
Currently the parameters include: largeProfile, largeDiameter, largeOpening, largeRotation, smallProfile, smallDiameter,  smallOpening, smallRotation, legProfile, springAngle, claspLength, claspGap, claspOffset, sleeveDiameter, sleevePadding, and sleeveStopSize. See the code for details!

1) Print. 
2) Use. 
3) Send CodeCreations a beer if you like it. 
WARNING: Do not use printed carabiners for rock climbing, high elevation window cleaning, cliff rescues, sailing, in the Mines of Moria, or anything else you need a real carabiner for. If you choose to ignore this warning, at least make sure your will is up to date and have already sent me a beer.

comments.text: Consider making a spring loaded sleeve version, where by the sleeve stays below the button stop (retainer) where a coil spring is used below the sleeve along with a wider top section of the sleeve that covers the top post of the carabiner in order to provide the closure.  A coil spring cover would also be required to protect the spring from interference.

description.text:
This mount enables bare micro AIO cameras like this one to be fitted in frames that accept 20mm or 19mm wide cameras, such as the RunCam Micro in the Quattrovolante Libero.

Design based on M2 screws and nuts.

Works fine in PLA, should work well with TPU too in case you want it to absorb vibrations.

1. Press-fit the camera in the mount to check for tolerances.
  2. If too tight, carefully heat up the sides of the mount with a lighter (half a second should do on such a small piece) and fit it again.
  3. Remove the camera and add some hot glue drops behind the mount's front lip and sides.
  4. Quickly press the camera in again to let the glue fix it in place.
  5. Optionally add another two drops of hot glue at the front top of the mount.

If hot glue is not an option you can also use a rubber band wrapped around the mount horizontally - loop one end behind the camera lenses, stretch it around behind the mount, and re-loop it on the other side of the lenses.

Buenas, voy a realizar este aporte a la comunidad, que es un encargo que me han realizado, que ha sido la construcción de una "Super" impresora CoreXY de grandes dimensiones,

básicamente tiene de dimensiones exteriores 660x660x540 aproximadamente, y un area de impresión de 533x494x450

Comparto, para el que quiera hacerla mas grande (no creo que se deba mucho mas) o mas pequeña, todos los archivos, que serán:

-Montaje completo IGS para importar en cualquier programa como solidworks
-Ficheros STL para imprimir, para el que no quiera complicarse
-Firmware Marlin modificado
-Perfil de impresión para Simplify 3d

Básicamente la máquina utiliza para el eje X e Y un sistema de guias lineales HIWIN originales, para manejar el extrusor E3D con boquilla de 0.5 para ganar un poco de velocidad de impresión,

la electrónica es una standar compatible con Marlin, una MKS GEN 1.4 con un firmware modificado para utilizar el segundo driver del extrusor2 para el segundo motor de Z.

Los motores de X,Y, extrusor son nema17 de 0.9 grados para ganar precisión.

Los motores de Z, son Nema23, para poder con el peso de la plataforma. Ambos con el cableado igual de largo en los 2, para evitar desincronizaciones y conectados cada uno a un driver independiente (y maximizar asi la potencia entregada).

Podria ponerse un segundo final de carrera en Z al otro lado, para autoconpensar la plataforma tras cada impresión.

El Z se mueve por varillas lisas + husillos con antibacklash, aunque es facil pasar la plataforma si se quiere a guias lineales.

El diseño del Z esta pensado para usar Nemas17 (piezas verdes) si se hace una plataforma mas ligera, o sino Nema23 (piezas amarillas)

La plataforma va calentada con 2 camas de silicona puenteadas , con 2 mosfets y 2 fuentes de alimentación. Solo se utiliza un termistor.

Mas o menos los costes nos vamos a cerca de los 900e comprando todo en españa. No tengo BOM de materiales, explico en video las compras.

  • If middle part is not moving well on sliding rods, polish them and use lubricant. If then is not moving well, use drill 4.0 - 4.1mm to clear holes for easier sliding. Or you can assembly professional sliding bearings here (e.g. from brass or IGUS)

description.text:
At Work we use a Mariner 3S ClubLiner Pool Robot to clean the Swimmingpool.
The Robot works great, but cleaning the Robot's Filters afterwards was always a mess, so i searched for a better way.

Its just a Piece of 16mm Plastic Conduit (EAN 4013960179804) with a Pipe coupling, three customized Airsoft Plastic Ball Bearings ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1799757 ) glued to the conduit, a thin Tip-Bearing glued on Top and a 16mm Mountable Stand - all mounted inside a big Bucket.

With the Filter stacked on top of the Conduit, i use a Garden Hose with a adjustable Nozzle to clean the Filter and let it rotate in the Water spray. I also made a hole in the Bucket to let the water out.

When the Filter spins it works like a Centrifuge and the Dirt, Sand and Hairs flies away, leaving a clean Filter. The Conduit can be easily removed from the Bucket for cleaning.

Works great and shold be (mostly) rustproof :-)

title: Magnetic build plate and bed leveling object

description.text:
DIY Magnetic build plate

Update February 15, 2018:
I am using an "Additional BuildTak FlexPlate" , https://www.buildtak.com/product/flexplate/ ,with PEI mounted on it. The original magnetic sheets mounted on the build plate remains intact. It holds great and there will be no horizontal slippage. However when I printed a large box with thick walls taking up almost the whole build area, I needed to add clips to prevent the print from lifting the corner of the flexplate. There is no problem with normal prints. The clips are only needed when there is potential of prints warping when they are close to the edges of the magnetic plate.

So, this is my final material list and I don't anticipate any more changes.
1) Additional BuildTak FlexPlate, https://www.buildtak.com/product/flexplate/
2) Gizmo Dorks PEI Sheet 12" x 12" 1 mm, https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B074XLD5QH
3) Corneria 10 Magnetic Sheets Adhesive 20 Mil Magnet, https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B003XNAHMC

If the amazon links don't take you to the product, copy the link text and paste it in your browser or search amazon for the descriptive text. Right now Thingiverse is doing something to the links so they don't take you to the product page.

Update December 18, 2017
I tested a large print, 260 x 295mm, with the PEI and it worked well. Once the magnetic PEI was lifted from the build plate the part just peeled off. The corner started to separate between the magnetic sheets so I put a clip on it. For large prints that are close to the corners it is advisable to use clips.

https://youtu.be/x4u3nnKkihU

Update November 29, 2017:
I have upgraded the build material to use PEI. It works great and lets me print PLA and ABS without glue stick or hair spray. The prints are so easy to remove when completed. This PEI is 1mm thin and is perfect to use with the magnetic sheets.
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B074XLD5QH/ . I tried using a 12 x 24 x 30mil magnetic sheet cut in half, hoping to avoid piecing the 8x10 material I used before. But the magnetic strength was poor and the adhesive was week. So, I used the same magnetic sheets, pieced together, that I have described below.

The video of this can be found at: https://youtu.be/S6XliO3rpnk

Original post, November 8, 2017:
I have a Maghold system on my QIDI Tech 1 and love it. I wanted something similar for my new CR-10S. I decided to make my own with https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B073TW738G Athorbot build surface and https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B003XNAHMC adhesive magnetic sheets. I'm sure most build surfaces and most magnetic sheets will work just fine. I also got a sheet of 0.03" polycarbonate (lexan) in case I need more stiffening, but the mag sheets attached directly to the build surface seems to work just fine.

I ditched the glass plate that came with the CR-10S and put the mag sheet directly on the aluminum bed. The bed seems to be a bit flatter without the extra weight of the glass bed. The glass plate weighs 919g while build surface with mag sheet weighs just 237g.
I use a coat of glue stick or hair spray to ensure the prints stick nicely. I've been using this for a few days and really like it. I'm using it with a bed temperature of 60C and don't know how well it'll hold up for high bed temps. Make sure the magnetic surfaces align the same way. If you look carefully at the magnetic side of the sheet you should see some regular linear pattern. This pattern should go the same way on both the bed and the build surface for all pieces.

The bed leveling objects make it easy to fine tune bed leveling. The cylinder is 25mm diameter with 1.6mm wall thickness and 0.2mm height. So you can check adhesion and fill for the first layer of your 3D printer. I copy to make five objects in my slicer, one for each of the leveling screws and one in the center of the Creality 10S 3D printer.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZGxUAbYhKrc&feature=youtu.be

description.text:
Charging stand for the Huawei Honor 6X and an Asus Zenwatch2. This is designed for the cord that came with my watch. You may have to modify the charging cord opening based on your cord(s). The phone cord that this is modeld for can be purchased here:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01M0LK2SK/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

The phone opening is designed to accept the phone in a case. The case that this is designed for can be purchased here:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01MG92TCO/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

If you use a different case or cord, there's a good chance you'll have to modify the stand.

Feed the phone cord through the hoop at the rear, then down through the hole in the bottom, through the groove, then up into the charger seat. For the watch cord, feed it through the hoop in the back, through the hole in the side, through the hole in the face, then into the charger seat. Friction should keep them in place for the most part, but i like to use a little hot glue to keep them in place until I need to remove them.

Use supports everywhere, to support all of the various openings. I printed mine at 20% infill.

A bonus with this design is that the front firing speaker hole seems to provide an increase in dB for the speaker. Makes it great for using your phone as your alarm.

title: Cord Clip for 2x18 AWG Split Wire

description.text:
Quick little clip to tidy the cord for the desktop fan we use when soldering. This kind of power cord is common in small ungrounded household appliances--for example, our Surebonder glue gun uses exactly the same kind of cord..

To check if this clip will fit your cord, look closely along the power cord for printed markings. You want "2X18AWG SPT-2" or "2X0.824mm^2 SPT-2".

Designed in Autodesk Fusion. Files include the STL file for printing and an export of the Fusion design file. Photo shows a clip printed in nGen Colorfabb on a Lulzbot Taz 6 using high detail, which took less than ten minutes.

description.text:
I use the cheap MPOW Bluetooth adapter with ear bud headphones, but the buttons would randomly press in my pocket. I whipped this up to make the buttons a little more difficult to press when in your pocket. Slides in and out easily, should be a friction fit. Holes for USB port, headphone jack, and button access.

Print with 0% infill, and as many solid bottom layers to make sure the bottom is filled in with 2 or 3 solid top layers. Just makes the walls more flexible and lighter (and print faster).

This is the MPOW bluetooth adapter I have/this is modeled for:
https://www.amazon.com/Mpow-Bluetooth-Receiver-Streaming-Hands-free/dp/B008AGQMQC/

May fit the newer version but I can't confirm.
